    ns1:inpersonHours "33 horas y 30 minutos (42.9%)"@es ;
    ns1:numberOfCredits 3.0 ;
    ns1:otherInformation "Please note that the schedule is indicative. The towing tank lab sessions will be carried out in groups, and a report must be prepared for each session. These sessions include a pre-lab quiz based on the practice guide to be used."@es ;
    ns1:periodEndingMonth "Enero"@es ;
    ns1:periodStartingMonth "Septiembre"@es ;
    ns1:teachingPeriod "2025-26" ;
    ns1:teachingPeriodMonths "Septiembre-Enero"@es ;
    ns1:totalHours "36 horas y 30 minutos"@es ;
    schema:activitiesWorkload "100%"@es ;
    schema:courseSchedule <https://guia-kg.skai.etsisi.upm.es/resource/83000139/2025-26/eventSchedule> ;
    schema:description """The course is structured into two main parts.
The first part covers general theoretical aspects of sloshing in rigid tanks. Topics include the governing equations, anti-roll tanks, vertical and horizontal sloshing, and the impact of sloshing on the damping of mechanical systems.

The second part introduces, through a practical approach, a computational method to simulate sloshing problems: the Smoothed Particle Hydrodynamics (SPH) method. For this purpose, students will use the AQUAgpusph code, developed at ETSIN.

This second part also includes a practical session at the Towing Tank of the ETSI Navales, where various experimental setups related to sloshing will be demonstrated (such as the Dam Break test, sloshing in single-degree-of-freedom systems, and anti-roll tanks).

Each student will select one of the sloshing problems presented and simulate it using SPH, comparing their results with existing references in the literature and other previously derived results."""@es ;
    schema:director <https://guia-kg.skai.etsisi.upm.es/resource/javier.calderon%40upm.es> ;
    schema:inLanguage "Inglés"@es ;
    schema:instructor <https://guia-kg.skai.etsisi.upm.es/resource/antonio.souto%40upm.es>,
        <https://guia-kg.skai.etsisi.upm.es/resource/javier.calderon%40upm.es> ;
    schema:name "Sloshing"@es .

